<h2>Requesting a Special Education Evaluation in Carrollton-Farmers Branch ISD</h2>
<p>This guide provides information on requesting a special education evaluation for your child in the Carrollton-Farmers Branch Independent School District (CFBISD). This process is governed by the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) and Texas state laws. Understanding these laws and procedures will empower you to advocate for your child's needs.</p>
<h3>How to Submit a Written Request</h3>
<p>The most important step in initiating the special education evaluation process is submitting a written request to the school. A verbal request, while it might alert school personnel, doesn't formally trigger the legal timelines and requirements outlined in IDEA and Texas Education Code (TEC).</p>
<p>Your written request should be clear, concise, and include the following information:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Date:</b> The date you are submitting the request. This date is crucial for tracking the timeline.</li>
<li><b>Child's Full Name and Date of Birth:</b> Ensure accuracy to avoid any confusion.</li>
<li><b>Child's Grade Level and Current School:</b> State your child's current academic placement within CFBISD.</li>
<li><b>Your Name, Address, Phone Number, and Email Address:</b> Provide multiple ways for the school to contact you.</li>
<li><b>Specific Concerns:</b> Clearly describe your concerns about your child's academic, behavioral, social-emotional, or physical development. Be as specific as possible. For example, instead of saying "My child is struggling in reading," state "My child is struggling to decode words, consistently scores below grade level on reading assessments, and has difficulty comprehending written material."</li>
<li><b>Examples of Difficulties:</b> Provide concrete examples of the difficulties your child is experiencing. Include observations from home and school. For instance, "At home, my child resists doing homework, becomes frustrated when asked to read aloud, and frequently asks for help with simple tasks." Or, "The teacher has reported that my child is frequently off-task, struggles to follow multi-step instructions, and has difficulty completing assignments within the allotted time."</li>
<li><b>Previous Interventions and Their Outcomes:</b> If your child has received any interventions, such as Response to Intervention (RTI), tutoring, or counseling, describe those interventions and their effectiveness. This demonstrates that you have already attempted to address your concerns.</li>
<li><b>Request for Evaluation:</b> Clearly state that you are requesting a full and individual initial evaluation to determine if your child has a disability and, if so, what special education and related services are needed. Use language like, "Therefore, I am requesting a full and individual initial evaluation under IDEA to determine if my child is eligible for special education services."</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Submitting the Request:</b> Deliver the written request to the school principal or the school's special education director. Keep a copy of the request for your records. Consider sending the request via certified mail with return receipt requested to have proof of delivery. This can be useful if there are any disagreements about when the request was received.</p>
<p><b>Example Request (Partial):</b></p>
<p>Date: October 26, 2023</p>
<p>To: [Principal's Name], Principal, [School Name]</p>
<p>From: [Your Name]</p>
<p>Subject: Request for Special Education Evaluation for [Child's Name]</p>
<p>I am writing to request a full and individual initial evaluation for my child, [Child's Name], who is a [Grade Level] student at [School Name]. [Child's Name]'s date of birth is [Date of Birth]. I am concerned about [Child's Name]'s difficulties in [Subject Area or Area of Concern]... [Continue with detailed description of concerns and examples].</p>
<h3>The 45 School Day Timeline</h3>
<p>Upon receiving your written request for an evaluation, CFBISD has a specific timeline to follow, as mandated by Texas law. This timeline is critical, and it's important to monitor the school's compliance.</p>
<p><b>Texas Administrative Code (TAC) §89.1011(c)</b> outlines the timeline. The school district has <b>45 school days</b> from the date they <b>receive</b> your written request to complete the following:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Obtain Parental Consent to Evaluate:</b> The school must request your written consent to proceed with the evaluation. This is typically done through a Permission to Evaluate form. They must make reasonable efforts to obtain your consent.</li>
<li><b>Complete the Full and Individual Initial Evaluation (FIE):</b> Conduct all necessary assessments to determine if your child has a disability.</li>
<li><b>Hold an Admission, Review, and Dismissal (ARD) Committee Meeting:</b> The ARD committee, which includes you, the parent, and school personnel, must meet to review the evaluation results and determine if your child is eligible for special education services.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Important Considerations:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><b>School Days vs. Calendar Days:</b> The 45-day timeline refers to school days, not calendar days. Weekends, holidays, and summer breaks are not included in the count.</li>
<li><b>Document Everything:</b> Keep a log of all communication with the school, including dates, times, and the content of conversations. This documentation will be valuable if any disputes arise.</li>
<li><b>Request a Copy of the Evaluation Report:</b> You are entitled to a copy of the FIE report prior to the ARD meeting. Request this report in advance so you have time to review it thoroughly.</li>
</ul>
<p>If the school fails to meet the 45-day timeline, you have the right to file a complaint with the Texas Education Agency (TEA). You can also pursue mediation or a due process hearing to address the delay.</p>
<h3>What the FIE Must Cover</h3>
<p>The Full and Individual Initial Evaluation (FIE) is a comprehensive assessment of your child's strengths and weaknesses across various areas of development. The purpose of the FIE is to determine if your child has a disability, and if so, to identify the specific educational needs that require special education and related services.</p>
<p>The FIE must be conducted by qualified professionals and should cover all areas related to the suspected disability. The specific areas assessed will vary depending on your child's individual needs and the concerns you raised in your written request. However, generally, the FIE may include assessments in the following areas:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Academic Achievement:</b> Reading (decoding, fluency, comprehension), writing (spelling, grammar, composition), and math (calculation, problem-solving). Standardized achievement tests are typically used.</li>
<li><b>Cognitive Abilities:</b> Intellectual functioning, learning style, memory, and attention. IQ tests (e.g., Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children - WISC) may be administered.</li>
<li><b>Language Skills:</b> Receptive language (understanding spoken language) and expressive language (using spoken language). Assessments may include tests of vocabulary, grammar, and communication skills.</li>
<li><b>Speech and Fluency:</b> Articulation, fluency (stuttering), and voice quality. Evaluated by a speech-language pathologist.</li>
<li><b>Motor Skills:</b> Gross motor skills (e.g., running, jumping) and fine motor skills (e.g., writing, buttoning). Evaluated by an occupational therapist or physical therapist.</li>
<li><b>Social-Emotional Functioning:</b> Social skills, emotional regulation, and behavior. Observations, interviews, and rating scales may be used.</li>
<li><b>Adaptive Behavior:</b> Daily living skills, such as self-care, communication, and socialization. Assessments may include adaptive behavior scales (e.g., Vineland Adaptive Behavior Scales).</li>
<li><b>Health and Medical History:</b> Review of medical records and consultation with medical professionals, if necessary.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Parent Involvement:</b> Your input is crucial throughout the FIE process. Share your observations, concerns, and any relevant information about your child's history and development with the evaluators. Ask questions about the assessments being used and how the results will be interpreted.</p>
<p><b>Independent Educational Evaluation (IEE):</b> You have the right to obtain an Independent Educational Evaluation (IEE) at public expense if you disagree with the school's evaluation. An IEE is conducted by a qualified professional who is not employed by the school district. To request an IEE at public expense, you must notify the school district in writing. The district must either agree to pay for the IEE or initiate a due process hearing to defend their evaluation.</p>
<h3>Child Find Obligations</h3>
<p>CFBISD has a legal obligation under IDEA and Texas law to actively identify, locate, and evaluate all children with disabilities within their jurisdiction, regardless of whether they are enrolled in public school. This is known as the "Child Find" mandate.</p>
<p><b>What This Means for You:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><b>Referrals from Outside Sources:</b> Child Find applies to children who are not yet enrolled in CFBISD schools, including those who are homeschooled or attend private schools. If you suspect your child has a disability, even if they are not attending a CFBISD school, you can still request an evaluation.</li>
<li><b>Awareness and Outreach:</b> CFBISD is required to conduct public awareness activities to inform parents about the availability of special education services. This may include distributing information through community organizations, healthcare providers, and early childhood programs.</li>
<li><b>Timely Evaluation:</b> Once a child is identified as potentially having a disability, the school district must promptly evaluate the child to determine eligibility for special education services. The same 45-school-day timeline applies.</li>
</ul>
<p>If you believe CFBISD is not fulfilling its Child Find obligations, you can file a complaint with the Texas Education Agency (TEA).</p>
<h3>What If They Refuse</h3>
<p>If CFBISD refuses to conduct an initial evaluation after you have submitted a written request, they must provide you with a written explanation of their reasons for the refusal. This written notice must comply with the procedural safeguards outlined in IDEA and Texas law.</p>
<p><b>Reasons for Refusal:</b> The school may refuse to evaluate if they believe there is insufficient evidence to suggest that your child has a disability or that your child's difficulties are primarily due to a lack of instruction or limited English proficiency. However, a refusal based on these grounds must be supported by data and documentation.</p>
<p><b>Your Rights if They Refuse:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><b>Request a Meeting:</b> Request a meeting with the school to discuss their reasons for refusing the evaluation. Bring any documentation you have to support your request.</li>
<li><b>Mediation:</b> Request mediation through the Texas Education Agency (TEA). Mediation is a voluntary process in which a neutral third party helps you and the school district reach an agreement.</li>
<li><b>Due Process Hearing:</b> File a request for a due process hearing with the TEA. A due process hearing is a formal legal proceeding in which an impartial hearing officer hears evidence and makes a decision about whether the school district violated your child's rights under IDEA.</li>
<li><b>State Complaint:</b> File a complaint with the Texas Education Agency (TEA). A state complaint is a formal written complaint alleging that the school district has violated a provision of IDEA or Texas special education law.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Document Everything:</b> Keep detailed records of all communication with the school, including dates, times, and the content of conversations. This documentation will be essential if you pursue any of the dispute resolution options listed above.</p>
<h3>After the Evaluation</h3>
<p>Once the FIE is complete, the ARD (Admission, Review, and Dismissal) committee will convene to discuss the evaluation results and determine whether your child meets the eligibility criteria for special education services under Texas law and IDEA.</p>
<p><b>The ARD Committee:</b> The ARD committee is a group of individuals responsible for making decisions about your child's special education program. The committee must include:</p>
<ul>
<li>You, the parent(s)</li>
<li>At least one regular education teacher of your child (if your child is participating in regular education)</li>
<li>At least one special education teacher of your child</li>
<li>A representative of the school district who is qualified to provide or supervise special education</li>
<li>A person who can interpret the instructional implications of evaluation results</li>
<li>Your child (when appropriate)</li>
<li>Other individuals who have knowledge or special expertise regarding your child (at your discretion or the district's discretion)</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Eligibility Determination:</b> The ARD committee will review the FIE results and determine if your child meets the criteria for one or more of the specific disability categories outlined in Texas Administrative Code (TAC) §89.1040. These categories include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Autism</li>
<li>Deaf-Blindness</li>
<li>Emotional Disturbance</li>
<li>Hearing Impairment</li>
<li>Intellectual Disability</li>
<li>Multiple Disabilities</li>
<li>Orthopedic Impairment</li>
<li>Other Health Impairment</li>
<li>Specific Learning Disability</li>
<li>Speech or Language Impairment</li>
<li>Traumatic Brain Injury</li>
<li>Visual Impairment</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Individualized Education Program (IEP):</b> If the ARD committee determines that your child is eligible for special education services, the committee will develop an Individualized Education Program (IEP). The IEP is a written document that outlines your child's specific educational needs, goals, and the services and supports they will receive. The IEP must be tailored to your child's individual needs and must be reviewed and revised at least annually.</p>
<p><b>Key Components of the IEP:</b></p>
<ul>
<li>Present Levels of Academic Achievement and Functional Performance (PLAAFP)</li>
<li>Measurable Annual Goals</li>
<li>Special Education and Related Services</li>
<li>Accommodations and Modifications</li>
<li>Assessment Modifications</li>
<li>Placement</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Your Role in the ARD Process:</b> You are an equal member of the ARD committee and have the right to participate fully in all decisions regarding your child's special education program. Don't hesitate to ask questions, express your concerns, and advocate for your child's needs.</p>
<p>This guide provides a general overview of the special education evaluation process in CFBISD. It is important to consult with legal counsel or advocacy organizations for personalized advice and support. The Texas Education Agency (TEA) website provides additional information and resources on special education laws and regulations.</p>
<section class="faq-section" style="margin:50px 0;">
<h2 style="font-size:1.4rem;margin-bottom:5px;">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<p style="color:#64748b;margin-bottom:20px;">Answers every parent in Texas needs to know.</p>
<details style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;padding:14px 0;">
<summary style="font-weight:600;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        How do I request a special education evaluation in Texas? <span style="font-size:1.3rem;color:#64748b;">+</span>
</summary>
<p style="margin:10px 0 0;color:#475569;line-height:1.7;">Submit a written request directly to the school's principal or special education director. The written request starts the mandatory 45 school-day clock. Keep a dated copy for your records.</p>
</details>
<details style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;padding:14px 0;">
<summary style="font-weight:600;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        What is a Full Individual Evaluation (FIE) in Texas? <span style="font-size:1.3rem;color:#64748b;">+</span>
</summary>
<p style="margin:10px 0 0;color:#475569;line-height:1.7;">A Full Individual Evaluation (FIE) is a comprehensive assessment the school must complete to determine if your child has a disability and needs special education services. It must cover all areas of suspected disability and be completed within 45 school days of your written consent.</p>
</details>
<details style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;padding:14px 0;">
<summary style="font-weight:600;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        Can a Texas school refuse to evaluate my child? <span style="font-size:1.3rem;color:#64748b;">+</span>
</summary>
<p style="margin:10px 0 0;color:#475569;line-height:1.7;">Yes, but only if the district provides written notice (Prior Written Notice) explaining why they are refusing and what data they relied on. You have the right to challenge that refusal through mediation or a due process hearing.</p>
</details>
</section>
